children.subject: what if the air force strikes them down ! :O

history.content:
Dear EECS community, 

It my pleasure to announce another successful balloon launch!
The balloon was put together, tested and launched by the team of EE39 “Hands on ham radio” class.  Two balloons were launched at 20min interval from each other around 11:30am this morning from the roof of Cory Hall. 
Both balloon appear to be safe, and broadcasting their position. 
As of this moment, the balloons are over Nevada, 80 miles east of Reno. They are traveling at an elevation of 26500’ at a velocity of 92MPH. 
Each balloon is equipped with 2 radios. A 1Watt VHF radio, which has a range of 150 Miles and reports accurate positions from the GPS.  It also has an HF, or short wave radio, which transmits coded messages at 10mWatts around 14MHz. These can be bounced off the ionosphere and have a range of up to 2000 miles. Unfortunately the positioning information from the HF radio is a 200miles square, but it would be useful for tracking the balloons over the ocean. 
Here’s a link to tracking the balloons: https://aprs.fi/#!call=a%2FNU6XB-12%2Ca%2FNU6XB-11%2Ca%2FNU6XB-13%2Ca%2FNU6XB-14&timerange=604800&tail=604800
NU6XB-11 and NU6XB-12 are the callsigns for the VHF and HF radios of balloon 1. 
NU6XB-13 and NU6XB-14 are the callsigns for the VHF and HF radios of balloon 2. 
Clicking on the balloons will give you more information—like velocity, height, voltage, number of received satellites and atmospheric pressure, including a message from the students. 
The predicted path is attached. Each Marker is 6 hours. 
More tomorrow!
— Miki
